and I'll give ya

502
00:34:06,987 --> 00:34:09,355
until you see
sense enough to stop.

503
00:34:09,389 --> 00:34:12,392
Or until I have no fingers left.

504
00:34:12,425 --> 00:34:14,527
Does this make things
clearer to ya?

505
00:34:15,662 --> 00:34:17,297
Not really, no.

506
00:34:17,330 --> 00:34:18,364
Because I don't want

507
00:34:18,398 --> 00:34:19,767
to hurt your feelings, Padraic.

508
00:34:19,800 --> 00:34:20,835
I don't, like.

509
00:34:21,568 --> 00:34:22,602
But it feels like the drastic

510
00:34:22,635 --> 00:34:24,071
is the only option
left open to me.

511
00:34:24,105 --> 00:34:26,606
You've loads of options
left open to ya.

512
00:34:26,639 --> 00:34:28,775
How's fingers
the first port of call?

513
00:34:28,808 --> 00:34:33,012
Please, don't talk to me

514
00:34:33,046 --> 00:34:36,015
no more, Padraic. Please.

515
00:34:36,049 --> 00:34:37,483
I'm begging you.

516
00:34:37,516 --> 00:34:39,418
But...
JONJO: Shush, like, Padraic.

517
00:34:39,451 --> 00:34:41,921
Just, you know, shush, like.
Yeah, I'd shush, like.

518
00:34:41,955 --> 00:34:43,723
I will shush.

519
00:34:46,092 --> 00:34:47,961
Except me and me sister
were thinking

520
00:34:47,994 --> 00:34:51,363
(SOFTLY) you might just be
a bit depressed, Colm.

521
00:34:51,396 --> 00:34:55,501
And I tell you this much,
fingers just confirms it.

522
00:34:56,468 --> 00:34:59,338
Don't you think, Colm?

523
00:35:00,907 --> 00:35:02,675
Starting from now.

524
00:35:15,053 --> 00:35:16,387
(DOOR OPENS)

525
00:35:19,258 --> 00:35:20,993
(DOOR CLOSES)

526
00:35:21,026 --> 00:35:22,527
Well, I never heard the like.

527
00:35:22,560 --> 00:35:24,930
I never heard the like. He
must really not like you, Padraic.

528
00:35:24,963 --> 00:35:26,297
Fingers!

529
00:35:26,330 --> 00:35:27,900
Jesus. He's serious, lads.

530
00:35:27,933 --> 00:35:28,834
JONJO: He is serious!

531
00:35:28,867 --> 00:35:30,668
You can see it
in his eyes he's serious.

532
00:35:30,702 --> 00:35:32,503
Just because
he thinks you're dull.

533
00:35:32,537 --> 00:35:33,972
That's going overboard!

534
00:35:34,006 --> 00:35:35,808
Who told you about the dull?

535
00:35:36,875 --> 00:35:38,243
Well, I overheard it.

536
00:35:38,277 --> 00:35:40,078
Like, what was I supposed to do?

537
00:35:40,112 --> 00:35:41,646
I don't think you're dull.

538
00:35:41,680 --> 00:35:43,816
And jeez, if I was
to cut something off meself

539
00:35:43,849 --> 00:35:47,652
for every dull person that came
in here, I'd only have me head left.

540
00:35:47,686 --> 00:35:49,054
Do you think I'm dull, Gerry?

541
00:35:49,087 --> 00:35:50,321
No.

542
00:35:51,890 --> 00:35:53,624
That said,

543
00:35:53,658 --> 00:35:57,129
I did think the two of ye always
made a funny pairing, like.

544
00:35:57,162 --> 00:35:59,197
No, we didn't.
JONJO: Yeah, ye did.

545
00:35:59,230 --> 00:36:00,765
Ye did. Obviously, ye did.

546
00:36:00,798 --> 00:36:03,667
'Cause now he'd rather
maim himself than talk to ya.

547
00:36:03,701 --> 00:36:05,970
Colm was always
more of a thinker.

548
00:36:06,003 --> 00:36:07,038
Huh?

549
00:36:07,071 --> 00:36:08,940
Why's every... I think.

550
00:36:08,973 --> 00:36:09,841
Ah, you don't, Padraic.

551
00:36:09,874 --> 00:36:11,608
You don't, Padraic.
Your sister does.

552
00:36:11,641 --> 00:36:13,610
Your sister does, aye.
Siobhan does. You're more of a...

553
00:36:13,643 --> 00:36:15,146
You're more of a...
What is he?

554
00:36:15,179 --> 00:36:17,181
You're more one
of life's good guys.

555
00:36:17,215 --> 00:36:19,349
You're more one
of life's good guys, aye.

556
00:36:19,382 --> 00:36:20,584
Apart from when you're drunk.

557
00:36:20,617 --> 00:36:22,887
Apart from when
you're drunk, aye.

558
00:36:22,920 --> 00:36:25,923
I used to think
that'd be a nice thing to be.

559
00:36:25,957 --> 00:36:27,959
One of life's good guys.

560
00:36:27,992 --> 00:36:30,728
And now, it sounds like
the worst thing I ever heard.

561
00:36:30,761 --> 00:36:32,230
Ah, don't take it
like that, Padraic.

562
00:36:32,263 --> 00:36:34,165
Don't take it
like that, Padraic.

563
00:36:34,198 --> 00:36:35,700
We're on your side.

564
00:36:37,034 --> 00:36:39,036
(GLOOMY MUSIC PLAYING)

565
00:36:49,445 --> 00:36:51,447
What are you smiling at?

566
00:36:57,921 --> 00:36:59,521
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

567
00:37:15,005 --> 00:37:18,507
What's this mope so mopey for?
He's just a fecking man, lads!

568
00:37:18,540 --> 00:37:20,143
A fat, ginger man!

569
00:37:21,077 --> 00:37:22,478
Ay yi yi.

570
00:37:22,511 --> 00:37:25,248
I'll tell ya this much.
Ye two are awful mopey hosts.

571
00:37:25,282 --> 00:37:27,950
Luckily, you won't have to put
up with us more than one night, so,

572
00:37:27,983 --> 00:37:29,718
and try eatin'
with your mouth closed.

573
00:37:29,752 --> 00:37:31,320
Where are we now, France?

574
00:37:31,353 --> 00:37:32,688
Will you tell him, Padraic?

575
00:37:32,721 --> 00:37:35,257
Aye, stop being a little
fecking bollocks, Dominic.

576
00:37:35,291 --> 00:37:37,492
No. Just about
the mouth thing.

577
00:37:39,460 --> 00:37:41,864
Colm Doherty
and his fat fecking fingers.

578
00:37:41,897 --> 00:37:43,032
He probably
wouldn't even be able

579
00:37:43,065 --> 00:37:45,367
to cut through the blubber
on them fingers.

580
00:37:45,401 --> 00:37:46,735
Would you not want him
to have to do the one finger

581
00:37:46,769 --> 00:37:48,270
to see if he was bluffing, like?

582
00:37:48,304 --> 00:37:49,405
No, we wouldn't.

583
00:37:49,437 --> 00:37:50,806
That's what I'd have him do,

584
00:37:50,839 --> 00:37:53,075
I'd have him do the one finger
to see if he was bluffin'.

585
00:37:53,108 --> 00:37:54,276
'Cause worst comes to worst,

586
00:37:54,310 --> 00:37:56,779
he can still play the fiddle
with four fingers, I'll bet ya.

587
00:37:56,812 --> 00:37:58,213
Or the banjo.

588
00:37:58,247 --> 00:37:59,348
We don't want any of that.

589
00:37:59,381 --> 00:38:00,716
We just want nothing
to do with him no more.

590
00:38:00,749 --> 00:38:02,918
You don't. This gom does.

591
00:38:03,518 --> 00:38:04,887
I am a gom, is right.

592
00:38:04,920 --> 00:38:07,156
You're not a gom!
(DOMINIC SIGHS)

593
00:38:08,489 --> 00:38:10,125
DOMINIC: Jeez.

594
00:38:10,159 --> 00:38:12,226
This is a depressing house.

595
00:38:12,260 --> 00:38:14,395
Would you prefer your own, so?

596
00:38:14,429 --> 00:38:16,197
I've heard it's a barrel
of fecking laughs.

597
00:38:17,031 --> 00:38:18,800
Well, touche.

598
00:38:19,267 --> 00:38:20,634
Too what?

599
00:38:20,668 --> 00:38:23,104
Che. Touche.
It's from the French.

600
00:38:35,817 --> 00:38:38,485
And how is it, Siobhan,
that you was never married?

601
00:38:42,423 --> 00:38:43,691
It's none of your
fecking business

602
00:38:43,725 --> 00:38:45,827
how I was never fecking married.

603
00:38:45,860 --> 00:38:46,928
How isn't it?

604
00:38:47,594 --> 00:38:48,997
How isn't it?

605
00:38:49,629 --> 00:38:50,898
Was you never wild?

606
00:38:51,665 --> 00:38:55,436
Wild? Was I never wild?

607
00:38:55,470 --> 00:38:57,304
I don't know what
you're talkin' about, Dominic.

608
00:38:57,337 --> 00:38:59,538
Wild, how? Angry?

609
00:38:59,572 --> 00:39:01,408
'Cause I'm gettin' angry now,
I can tell ya!

610
00:39:01,441 --> 00:39:02,843
Not angry. Wild.

611
00:39:02,876 --> 00:39:04,643
You just keep
sayin' wild, Dominic!

612
00:39:04,678 --> 00:39:06,346
Wild! My brother
told you, didn't he?

613
00:39:06,380 --> 00:39:07,546
That you'd be out in the road

614
00:39:07,580 --> 00:39:09,483
if you started
talking stupid to me?

615
00:39:09,515 --> 00:39:11,118
He said creepy, not stupid.

616
00:39:11,151 --> 00:39:13,086
Well, you've failed
on both counts, haven't ya?

617
00:39:13,120 --> 00:39:14,121
I have.

618
00:39:16,256 --> 00:39:18,524
I'm off to bed and he's not
stayin' here another night, Padraic.

619
00:39:18,557 --> 00:39:20,327
I don't care
how depressed you are.

620
00:39:20,360 --> 00:39:22,129
I'd rather have the donkey in.

621
00:39:23,596 --> 00:39:24,798
(DOOR SHUTS)

622
00:39:27,334 --> 00:39:29,369
Foiled again.

623
00:39:29,403 --> 00:39:31,537
But "faint heart" and all that.

624
00:39:40,113 --> 00:39:41,113
Here.

625
00:39:42,481 --> 00:39:45,251
Ye two, ye'll be all right.

626
00:39:47,053 --> 00:39:48,120
Will we be?

627
00:39:54,427 --> 00:39:56,628
(MELLOW MUSIC PLAYING)

628
00:40:05,404 --> 00:40:06,839
(CLICKING TONGUE)

629
00:40:37,368 --> 00:40:38,970
Hello there, Mrs. O'Riordan,
I've the milk outside for ya.

630
00:40:39,003 --> 00:40:40,805
So, it's the two weeks
you owe me for now, I think.

631
00:40:40,839 --> 00:40:42,273
Nobody has a lick of news

632
00:40:42,307 --> 00:40:44,976
for us from your side
of the island, Padraic.

633
00:40:45,009 --> 00:40:46,511
Are you going
to be the same as them?

634
00:40:46,544 --> 00:40:47,779
I am, Mrs. O'Riordan,
I'm afraid.

635
00:40:47,812 --> 00:40:49,714
And I'm in a bit
of a rush, so...

636
00:40:49,747 --> 00:40:52,851
Eileen Coughlan had no news.

637
00:40:52,884 --> 00:40:55,253
Vincent Shaughnessy had no news.

638
00:40:55,286 --> 00:40:57,922
It was a poor old week for
news. But then it is, sometimes.

639
00:40:57,956 --> 00:41:01,292
ColmSonnyLarry, he had no news.

640
00:41:01,326 --> 00:41:02,594
Did he not?

641
00:41:02,626 --> 00:41:04,496
That man never talks.

642
00:41:04,529 --> 00:41:06,197
Eh, he talks sometimes.
Up himself.

643
00:41:06,231 --> 00:41:09,100
Aye, aye, anyways, so, it's the two
weeks you owe me for now, Mrs. O'Riordan.

644
00:41:09,134 --> 00:41:10,400
As I was sayin'.

645
00:41:10,434 --> 00:41:11,702
(REGISTER DINGS)

646
00:41:15,139 --> 00:41:16,173
Ladies.

647
00:41:16,206 --> 00:41:17,040
Oh, it's Peadar.

648
00:41:17,074 --> 00:41:19,276
Peadar always
has a rake of news.

649
00:41:19,309 --> 00:41:22,045
What news have you, Peadar?
PEADAR: News, is it?

650
00:41:22,079 --> 00:41:24,848
Fella killed himself,
over Rosmuck way.

651
00:41:24,882 --> 00:41:26,783
Walked into a lake for himself.

652
00:41:26,817 --> 00:41:29,486
Twenty-nine and nothing wrong
with him, the fool.

653
00:41:29,520 --> 00:41:30,988
God love us!

654
00:41:31,021 --> 00:41:33,423
PEADAR: No,
not "God love us." Fool!

655
00:41:33,457 --> 00:41:34,558
Another fella,

656
00:41:34,591 --> 00:41:36,026
Protestant, of course,

657
00:41:36,059 --> 00:41:38,462
stabbed his missus
in Letterkenny.

658
00:41:38,495 --> 00:41:40,364
Six times he stabbed her.

659
00:41:40,397 --> 00:41:42,733
Good God!
And did she die, Peadar?

660
00:41:42,766 --> 00:41:44,234
She did die, aye.

661
00:41:44,268 --> 00:41:46,503
It wasn't with a spoon
he was stabbin' her.

662
00:41:46,537 --> 00:41:47,971
That's a lot of news.

663
00:41:48,005 --> 00:41:51,608
This man has no news,
don't ya not? No-Newsy!

664
00:41:51,642 --> 00:41:52,876
(PEADAR LAUGHS)

665
00:41:52,910 --> 00:41:55,044
Stukes never have news.
MRS. O'RIORDAN: Stukes!

666
00:41:55,077 --> 00:41:56,212
(LAUGHS) Funny.

667
00:41:56,245 --> 00:41:59,582
There was a bit of news
I remembered, Mrs. O'Riordan.

668
00:41:59,615 --> 00:42:01,717
Dominic Kearney's father
beat Dominic senseless

669
00:42:01,751 --> 00:42:03,052
with a kettle Saturday,

670
00:42:03,085 --> 00:42:04,987
and is staying with me
and me sister, Dominic is.

671
00:42:05,021 --> 00:42:06,722
So, at least his father'll
take a bit of a break

672
00:42:06,756 --> 00:42:07,957
from his beatin' of him.

673
00:42:08,691 --> 00:42:10,660
And him, a policeman.

674
00:42:10,693 --> 00:42:12,762
Isn't that news?

675
00:42:12,795 --> 00:42:15,431
Ar, that Dominic's
an awful little bollocks.

676
00:42:15,464 --> 00:42:16,632
That's no news.

677
00:42:16,667 --> 00:42:18,968
Still, he was in a bad way
when I came upon him.

678
00:42:19,001 --> 00:42:21,337
I'd beat him with a kettle
meself if I wasn't old.

679
00:42:21,370 --> 00:42:23,706
It's news is all I'm sayin'.

680
00:42:23,739 --> 00:42:25,975
That's no news.
That's shite news.

681
00:42:26,008 --> 00:42:28,044
Okay, so, Mrs. O'Riordan,
thanks for the...

682
00:42:28,679 --> 00:42:30,346
I'll see ya when I see ya.

683
00:42:33,583 --> 00:42:34,784
(DOOR THUDS, BELL RINGS)

684
00:42:37,386 --> 00:42:39,388
(BIRDS SQUAWK IN DISTANCE)

685
00:42:49,364 --> 00:42:50,365
(THUDS)

686
00:42:52,067 --> 00:42:53,802
And you can tell
that skitter of a son of mine

687
00:42:53,835 --> 00:42:55,337
he'd better be home by teatime,

688
00:42:55,370 --> 00:42:57,673
or it's over to batter
the both of ye I'll be,

689
00:42:57,707 --> 00:42:59,407
and your dreary
fecking sister, too!

690
00:43:03,245 --> 00:43:04,246
(GROANS)

691
00:43:09,884 --> 00:43:11,253
Oh, hello there, Colm.

692
00:43:11,286 --> 00:43:13,922
Will I see you at Jonjo's
tonight for that pint you owe me?

693
00:43:13,955 --> 00:43:15,390
I owe you no pin...

694
00:43:16,291 --> 00:43:17,392
You will, Peadar.

695
00:43:17,425 --> 00:43:18,893
Good man yourself.

696
00:43:25,466 --> 00:43:27,468
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING)

697
00:44:05,906 --> 00:44:08,208
(SOFT MUSIC CONTINUES)

698
00:44:22,121 --> 00:44:23,456
(SOBBING)

699
00:44:30,330 --> 00:44:31,964
Whoa, stand.

700
00:44:32,532 --> 00:44:33,533
Stand.

701
00:44:58,725 --> 00:45:00,325
(MELODIOUS FIDDLE
MUSIC PLAYING)

702
00:45:38,797 --> 00:45:39,997
(EXHALES)

703
00:45:43,401 --> 00:45:44,602
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

704
00:46:08,058 --> 00:46:10,261
(GENTLE MUSIC PLAYING)

705
00:46:12,196 --> 00:46:13,665
(WHISPERING)
What's that, Jenny?

706
00:46:15,734 --> 00:46:17,501
Will we go to the pub
for ourselves?

707
00:46:19,103 --> 00:46:20,705
We will. Come on.

708
00:46:37,620 --> 00:46:40,223
One drink you're havin', lady,
then it's off home with ya.

709
00:46:40,256 --> 00:46:43,126
I've a shirt that
wants ironing for the morning.

710
00:46:44,494 --> 00:46:46,095
Okay, Daddy.

711
00:46:46,129 --> 00:46:49,499
Aye. Off to the mainland
in the morning I'm headin'.

712
00:46:49,532 --> 00:46:51,669
That's why I need
the clean shirt, like.

713
00:46:53,369 --> 00:46:55,538
"And why are you off to the
mainland in the mornin', Peadar?"

714
00:46:55,572 --> 00:46:58,441
Oh, thanks for asking, Colm.
I'll tell ya why.

715
00:46:58,475 --> 00:47:00,076
They've asked for extra manpower

716
00:47:00,109 --> 00:47:02,078
for a couple of the
(WHISPERS) executions

717
00:47:02,111 --> 00:47:04,347
(NORMALLY) in case there's
any kind of a to-do, like.

718
00:47:04,380 --> 00:47:06,951
Six bob and a free lunch
they're payin' me.

719
00:47:06,983 --> 00:47:09,051
And sure I'd have gone
for nothin'.

720
00:47:09,084 --> 00:47:11,955
I've always wanted to see
an execution, haven't you?

721
00:47:11,987 --> 00:47:13,890
Although, I'd have
preferred a hanging.

722
00:47:13,923 --> 00:47:15,390
Who are they executin'?

723
00:47:15,424 --> 00:47:18,661
The Free State lads are
executin' a couple of the IRA lads.

724
00:47:20,095 --> 00:47:21,731
Or is it the other way around?

725
00:47:22,364 --> 00:47:23,198
(SCOFFS)

726
00:47:23,232 --> 00:47:25,869
I find it hard
to follow these days.

727
00:47:25,902 --> 00:47:28,203
Wasn't it so much easier when
we was all on the same side,

728
00:47:28,237 --> 00:47:30,305
and it was just the English
we was killin'?

729
00:47:30,339 --> 00:47:33,175
I think it was.
I preferred it.

730
00:47:33,208 --> 00:47:35,244
But you don't care
who's executin' who?

731
00:47:35,277 --> 00:47:37,579
For six bob and a free lunch,
I don't care!

732
00:47:37,613 --> 00:47:39,716
They could be
executin' you. (CHUCKLES)

733
00:47:40,717 --> 00:47:42,184
Why don't you come with me?

734
00:47:42,217 --> 00:47:44,721
You could write a miserable
feckin' song about it.

735
00:47:47,623 --> 00:47:49,191
Nah, I'm only messin'.

736
00:47:49,224 --> 00:47:51,593
(MUFFLED FOLK MUSIC PLAYING)

737
00:48:14,716 --> 00:48:15,616
Who are them?

738
00:48:15,650 --> 00:48:18,352
Music students, I think,
from Lisdoonvarna.

739
00:48:20,923 --> 00:48:22,290
(TALKING INDISTINCTLY)

740
00:48:30,197 --> 00:48:32,701
Another whiskey, anyways, Jonjo.

741
00:48:32,734 --> 00:48:35,938
Jeez, you're goin' at it at a
fair old lick tonight, Padraic.

742
00:48:35,971 --> 00:48:38,371
Yeah? What's it to ya?

743
00:48:38,973 --> 00:48:40,675
(DRUM INTRO PLAYS)

744
00:48:44,912 --> 00:48:47,247
(PLAYING TRADITIONAL
MARCH MUSIC)

745
00:49:09,135 --> 00:49:10,637
Padraic, don't now...

746
00:49:14,274 --> 00:49:15,810
Go get Siobhan,
Dominic, would ya?

747
00:49:17,678 --> 00:49:19,646
(DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES)

748
00:49:19,680 --> 00:49:21,681
PEADAR: What are you
after, gobshite?

749
00:49:21,715 --> 00:49:23,115
Another beatin', is it?

750
00:49:23,148 --> 00:49:25,451
You, copper, I'm allowed
to chat to you, aren't I?

751
00:49:25,484 --> 00:49:27,553
It's just tubbyguts
I'm not allowed to talk to.

752
00:49:27,586 --> 00:49:29,723
Actually, no, I'd rather
you didn't talk to me neither.

753
00:49:30,824 --> 00:49:32,157
Oh, well, anyways,

754
00:49:32,191 --> 00:49:35,028
do you want to know what the
three things that I hate the most

755
00:49:35,061 --> 00:49:36,428
on Inisherin is?
Not really.

756
00:49:36,763 --> 00:49:37,831
One,

757
00:49:38,798 --> 00:49:39,799
policemen.

758
00:49:40,767 --> 00:49:42,102
Two,

759
00:49:42,134 --> 00:49:43,335
pudgy fiddle players.

760
00:49:44,370 --> 00:49:46,438
And three... (VOICE CRACKS)

761
00:49:46,472 --> 00:49:48,842
Wait, I had some funny thing
for three. What was it?

762
00:49:48,875 --> 00:49:51,778
Uh, I'll start again. One, um,

763
00:49:51,811 --> 00:49:52,946
policemen.

764
00:49:52,979 --> 00:49:54,380
Two...

765
00:49:55,882 --> 00:49:57,050
Pudgy fiddle players.

766
00:49:57,083 --> 00:49:59,251
PADRAIC: Pudgy fiddle players.

767
00:49:59,284 --> 00:50:00,754
And shite, what was three?

768
00:50:00,787 --> 00:50:02,989
Go on back to your own gang
now, Padraic. I'm serious, now.

769
00:50:03,023 --> 00:50:04,289
(SHOUTING) Serious, are ya?

770
00:50:05,557 --> 00:50:06,424
(MUSIC HALTS)

771
00:50:06,457 --> 00:50:09,193
And talkin' to me, are ya?

772
00:50:11,063 --> 00:50:12,296
DOMINIC: Siobhan!

773
00:50:14,700 --> 00:50:17,069
Padraic's out of his brains
on whiskey, and Colm's there.

774
00:50:17,102 --> 00:50:18,636
You'd better come.

775
00:50:25,476 --> 00:50:28,246
You, Colm Doherty, do you
know what you used to be?

776
00:50:28,279 --> 00:50:30,448
No, Padraic,
what did I used to be?

777
00:50:30,481 --> 00:50:31,549
Nice!

778
00:50:32,151 --> 00:50:33,819
You used to be nice!

779
00:50:34,285 --> 00:50:36,220
Didn't he not?

780
00:50:36,254 --> 00:50:38,556
And now,
do you know what you are?

781
00:50:38,891 --> 00:50:39,992
Not nice.

782
00:50:40,025 --> 00:50:41,827
Ah, well,

783
00:50:41,860 --> 00:50:45,664
I suppose niceness doesn't
last then, does it, Padraic?

784
00:50:45,698 --> 00:50:47,532
But will I tell ya something
that does last?

785
00:50:47,565 --> 00:50:50,334
What? And don't say
somethin' stupid like music.

786
00:50:50,367 --> 00:50:52,469
Music lasts.
Knew it!

787
00:50:52,502 --> 00:50:55,439
And paintings last.
And poetry lasts.

788
00:50:55,472 --> 00:50:57,574
So does niceness.
(DOOR OPENS)

789
00:51:00,410 --> 00:51:01,545
COLM: Do you know
who we remember

790
00:51:01,578 --> 00:51:04,082
for how nice they was
in the 17th century?

791
00:51:04,115 --> 00:51:06,383
PADRAIC: Who?
Absolutely no one.

792
00:51:06,416 --> 00:51:09,486
Yet we all remember
the music of the time.

793
00:51:09,519 --> 00:51:11,588
Everyone, to a man,
knows Mozart's name.

794
00:51:11,621 --> 00:51:13,925
Well, I don't,
so there goes that theory.

795
00:51:14,892 --> 00:51:17,662
And anyway,
we're talkin' about niceness.

796
00:51:18,096 --> 00:51:19,596
Not whatsisname.

797
00:51:20,732 --> 00:51:22,934
My mammy, she was nice.

798
00:51:23,868 --> 00:51:25,837
I remember her.

799
00:51:25,870 --> 00:51:28,438
And my daddy, he was nice.
I remember him.

800
00:51:28,472 --> 00:51:31,341
And my sister, she's nice.

801
00:51:31,374 --> 00:51:34,679
I'll remember her.
Forever I'll remember her.

802
00:51:34,712 --> 00:51:37,246
COLM: And who else will?
PADRAIC: "Who else will" what?

803
00:51:37,279 --> 00:51:39,750
Remember Siobhan
and your niceness?

804
00:51:40,650 --> 00:51:41,651
No one will.

805
00:51:42,152 --> 00:51:43,252
In 50 years' time,

806
00:51:43,285 --> 00:51:45,621
no one will remember any of us.

807
00:51:47,490 --> 00:51:50,193
Yet the music of a man
who lived two centuries ago...

808
00:51:50,227 --> 00:51:52,461
"Yet," he says,
like he's English.

809
00:51:53,362 --> 00:51:54,563
Come home, Padraic.

810
00:51:54,597 --> 00:51:58,267
I don't give a feck
about Mozart,

811
00:51:58,735 --> 00:52:00,137
or Borvoven,

812
00:52:00,170 --> 00:52:03,405
or any of them
funny name feckers.

813
00:52:03,439 --> 00:52:05,407
I'm Padraic Suilleabhain.

814
00:52:07,276 --> 00:52:09,212
And I'm nice.

815
00:52:09,246 --> 00:52:10,747
SIOBHAN: (WHISPERS) Come home.

816
00:52:10,781 --> 00:52:13,616
So you'd rather be friends
with this fella, would ya?

817
00:52:14,017 --> 00:52:15,185
A fella who

818
00:52:15,218 --> 00:52:17,020
beats his own son
black and blue every night

819
00:52:17,053 --> 00:52:18,054
that he's not fiddling with him.

820
00:52:19,588 --> 00:52:22,624
I never told him that, Daddy.
He's... He's just drunk now.

821
00:52:23,125 --> 00:52:24,894
You used to be nice.

822
00:52:26,228 --> 00:52:27,930
Or did you never used to be?

823
00:52:30,800 --> 00:52:31,967
Oh, God.

824
00:52:34,670 --> 00:52:36,906
Maybe you never used to be.

825
00:52:50,451 --> 00:52:51,987
(DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES)

826
00:52:53,321 --> 00:52:54,857
I'll have a word with him, Colm.

827
00:52:54,890 --> 00:52:57,325
You don't need
to do anything drastic.

828
00:52:57,358 --> 00:52:59,195
He won't be
botherin' you no more.

829
00:52:59,228 --> 00:53:00,663
That's a shame.

830
00:53:01,664 --> 00:53:03,464
That's the most interesting
he's ever been.

831
00:53:03,498 --> 00:53:05,033
I think I like him again now.

832
00:53:05,066 --> 00:53:06,433
(MAN CHUCKLES)

833
00:53:08,502 --> 00:53:12,339
It was the 18th century,
anyway. Mozart.

834
00:53:12,841 --> 00:53:14,474
Not the 17th.

835
00:53:19,479 --> 00:53:22,650
(DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES)

836
00:53:23,117 --> 00:53:25,186
(RAIN PATTERING)

837
00:53:25,220 --> 00:53:27,421
(GLOOMY MUSIC PLAYING)

838
00:53:32,694 --> 00:53:33,761
(SIGHS)

839
00:53:49,877 --> 00:53:52,813
Siobhan Suilleabhain!
Well, well.

840
00:53:52,846 --> 00:53:54,748
I only came in for rashers,
Mrs. O'Riordan.

841
00:53:54,781 --> 00:53:56,216
I've no time to talk,
I'm afraid.

842
00:53:56,250 --> 00:53:57,751
Letter came for ya.

843
00:54:00,921 --> 00:54:02,421
Fell open, did it?

844
00:54:02,455 --> 00:54:03,957
Aye, in the heat, I suppose.

845
00:54:05,225 --> 00:54:06,425
(SIGHS)

846
00:54:10,463 --> 00:54:11,899
A job offer, is it?

847
00:54:18,571 --> 00:54:22,743
A job offer from a library
on the mainland, is it?

848
00:54:22,776 --> 00:54:26,647
Just the rashers, please, Mrs.
O'Riordan. About ten of them.

849
00:54:34,552 --> 00:54:36,756
You never tell me anything!

850
00:54:38,925 --> 00:54:41,027
Well, it'd crucify him,
your leaving!

851
00:54:41,060 --> 00:54:42,695
Hey, no one's leaving!

852
00:54:57,542 --> 00:54:59,078
Listen, I didn't
come down to chat.

853
00:54:59,111 --> 00:55:01,213
I just came down to say
that all that last night

854
00:55:01,247 --> 00:55:02,648
was just
the whiskey talkin', Colm.

855
00:55:02,682 --> 00:55:03,783
All what last night?

856
00:55:03,816 --> 00:55:06,085
All whatever it was
I was sayin'.

857
00:55:06,118 --> 00:55:07,219
What were you sayin'?

858
00:55:07,253 --> 00:55:09,989
Uh... Yeah.
I can't remember much of it,

859
00:55:10,022 --> 00:55:12,692
but I remember the gist
of it wasn't the best.

860
00:55:12,725 --> 00:55:14,727
You always know, don't ya?

861
00:55:17,830 --> 00:55:20,732
Well, anyways, I just wanted
to say I was sorry.

862
00:55:20,765 --> 00:55:22,033
Will we leave it at that?

863
00:55:23,735 --> 00:55:25,770
Why can't you just
leave me alone, Padraic?

864
00:55:26,905 --> 00:55:28,472
PADRAIC: Huh?

865
00:55:28,505 --> 00:55:30,375
I've already told ya, haven't I?

866
00:55:30,408 --> 00:55:31,843
Yeah, I know. I was just...

867
00:55:31,876 --> 00:55:34,079
I mean, why can't you
just leave me alone?

868
00:55:46,424 --> 00:55:48,126
What are ya doing?
I don't know.

869
00:55:49,260 --> 00:55:51,029
For fuck's sake, like.

870
00:55:59,503 --> 00:56:00,872
How... How's the new tune?

871
00:56:01,840 --> 00:56:02,840
What?

872
00:56:13,516 --> 00:56:15,953
(DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES)

873
00:56:16,787 --> 00:56:19,390
Ar, for God's sake, Padraic.

874
00:56:19,423 --> 00:56:20,724
How many more times?

875
00:56:20,758 --> 00:56:24,094
I am not putting me donkey
outside when I am sad, okay?

876
00:56:24,128 --> 00:56:26,296
Well, stringy bits of shite
I had to pick up

877
00:56:26,330 --> 00:56:27,597
yesterday when ya let her in!

878
00:56:27,630 --> 00:56:29,700
There was no stringy bits
in that donkey's shite.

879
00:56:29,733 --> 00:56:32,169
There was bits of straw,
if there was anything.

880
00:56:32,202 --> 00:56:34,004
Maybe it was straw, so.

881
00:56:35,605 --> 00:56:38,075
(SIGHS) I'll get us
our porridge.

882
00:56:57,360 --> 00:56:58,593
Was I awful last night?

883
00:57:01,664 --> 00:57:03,900
No, you was lovely.

884
00:57:03,933 --> 00:57:06,402
Well, I know I wasn't lovely
now, Siobhan. (CHUCKLES)

885
00:57:06,436 --> 00:57:08,871
You were lovely.
About me, anyways.

886
00:57:08,905 --> 00:57:12,008
Of course
I was lovely about you.

887
00:57:12,041 --> 00:57:13,643
What else is there
to be about ya?

888
00:57:13,676 --> 00:57:15,011
(SIOBHAN CHUCKLES)

889
00:57:15,044 --> 00:57:16,045
(DOOR THUDS)

890
00:57:26,856 --> 00:57:29,292
(SOFT SUSPENSEFUL
MUSIC PLAYING)

891
00:58:19,707 --> 00:58:21,142
What was that? A bird?

892
00:58:22,109 --> 00:58:23,544
What was what?

893
00:58:23,577 --> 00:58:24,912
The bang at the door.

894
00:58:25,346 --> 00:58:26,413
A bird?

895
00:58:26,447 --> 00:58:27,648
Aye.
No.

896
00:58:29,183 --> 00:58:30,284
What was it, so?

897
00:58:30,317 --> 00:58:31,619
The bang at the door?
Aye!

898
00:58:31,652 --> 00:58:33,387
What was the bang
at the door? (SCOFFS)

899
00:58:33,420 --> 00:58:35,422
It was, uh...

900
00:58:35,456 --> 00:58:36,557
hard to lie...

901
00:58:36,590 --> 00:58:39,126
it was, uh...

902
00:58:39,160 --> 00:58:41,896
(HESITATES) a finger.

903
00:58:42,696 --> 00:58:44,064
(CHUCKLES)

904
00:58:45,466 --> 00:58:46,667
A what?

905
00:58:47,034 --> 00:58:48,035
Finger.

906
00:58:48,469 --> 00:58:49,703
(SHRIEKS)

907
00:58:49,737 --> 00:58:51,472
Jesus, Siobhan! You'll
frighten the little fella!

908
00:58:51,505 --> 00:58:52,907
Throw it out, Padraic!

909
00:58:52,940 --> 00:58:55,109
I'm not throwing his
finger out! It'll get dirt on it!

910
00:58:55,142 --> 00:58:56,744
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

911
00:58:58,812 --> 00:59:00,047
Where... Where'd you put it?

912
00:59:02,015 --> 00:59:03,449
Shoebox.

913
00:59:03,483 --> 00:59:05,585
Oh, my. Oh, God.

914
00:59:05,618 --> 00:59:06,819
Well,

915
00:59:07,820 --> 00:59:09,189
he's serious, then.

916
00:59:26,272 --> 00:59:28,708
(PLAYING MELODIOUS TUNE)

917
01:00:26,098 --> 01:00:27,966
Do we have to have it in here
while we're eating?

918
01:00:28,000 --> 01:00:30,335
Once I finish me porridge,
I'll bring it back to him.

919
01:00:30,369 --> 01:00:32,136
(SCOFFS)

920
01:00:32,169 --> 01:00:35,473
(CHUCKLES IN DISBELIEF)
Are you feckin' stupid?

921
01:00:35,506 --> 01:00:38,376
I mean, are you feckin' stupid?

922
01:00:38,409 --> 01:00:40,511
No, I'm not feckin' stupid.
We've had this discussion.

923
01:00:40,544 --> 01:00:43,848
You've got to leave him
alone now, Padraic. For good!

924
01:00:44,683 --> 01:00:45,717
Do you think?

925
01:00:45,751 --> 01:00:48,085
Do I think? Yeah, I do think!

926
01:00:48,119 --> 01:00:50,955
He's cut his feckin' finger
off, and thrown it at ya!

927
01:00:50,988 --> 01:00:53,190
Come on! It wasn't at me.

928
01:00:55,126 --> 01:00:57,361
Well, what are we going to do?

929
01:00:57,395 --> 01:00:59,430
We can't keep a man's finger.

930
01:01:07,371 --> 01:01:08,372
(DOOR SHUTS)

931
01:01:16,379 --> 01:01:18,181
(RIFLE FIRING IN DISTANCE)

932
01:01:25,622 --> 01:01:27,524
Jesus, Colm!

933
01:01:28,726 --> 01:01:30,293
Did it hurt?

934
01:01:30,327 --> 01:01:33,363
(SCOFFS) Hurt awful to begin
with. Thought I was going to faint.

935
01:01:34,931 --> 01:01:38,568
It's funny, feels fine now,
in all the excitement.

936
01:01:40,705 --> 01:01:42,072
Would you like a cup of tea?

937
01:01:42,105 --> 01:01:45,241
I won't, Colm. I only came up
to give you your finger back.

938
01:01:45,743 --> 01:01:47,077
Oh, yeah?

939
01:01:48,478 --> 01:01:49,546
Thanks.

940
01:01:51,014 --> 01:01:53,249
Cleared up quite nice, actually.

941
01:01:53,283 --> 01:01:55,885
And you wouldn't
have thought it would.

942
01:01:55,919 --> 01:01:58,488
What do you need from him, Colm?

943
01:01:58,521 --> 01:02:00,089
To end all this?

944
01:02:03,325 --> 01:02:04,893
Silence, Siobhan.

945
01:02:05,494 --> 01:02:07,831
Just silence.

946
01:02:07,863 --> 01:02:12,601
One more silent man
on Inisherin, good-oh!

947
01:02:12,634 --> 01:02:14,236
Silence it is, so.

948
01:02:16,605 --> 01:02:18,808
This isn't about Inisherin.

949
01:02:18,842 --> 01:02:19,875
It's about one boring man

950
01:02:19,908 --> 01:02:21,845
leaving another man alone,
that's all.

951
01:02:21,877 --> 01:02:25,514
"One boring man"!
You're all fecking boring!

952
01:02:25,547 --> 01:02:28,550
With your piddling grievances
over nothin'!

953
01:02:28,584 --> 01:02:31,453
You're all fecking boring!

954
01:02:32,321 --> 01:02:35,057
I'll see he doesn't talk
to you no more.

955
01:02:35,090 --> 01:02:36,625
Do.

956
01:02:36,659 --> 01:02:40,295
Else it'll be all four of them
the next time, not just the one.

957
01:02:41,397 --> 01:02:42,965
You're not serious.

958
01:02:45,099 --> 01:02:47,535
Well, that won't help
your fecking music.

959
01:02:48,369 --> 01:02:49,838
Aye.

960
01:02:49,872 --> 01:02:51,472
We're gettin' somewhere now.

961
01:02:53,809 --> 01:02:57,813
(CHUCKLES) I think
you might be ill, Colm.

962
01:02:57,846 --> 01:02:58,980
(CHUCKLES LIGHTLY)

963
01:02:59,013 --> 01:03:02,583
Do worry sometimes
I'm just entertaining meself

964
01:03:02,617 --> 01:03:04,552
while I stave off
the inevitable.

965
01:03:06,487 --> 01:03:07,622
Don't you?

966
01:03:09,858 --> 01:03:11,660
No, I don't.

967
01:03:14,395 --> 01:03:15,596
Yeah, you do.

968
01:03:35,982 --> 01:03:38,185
(MELLOW MUSIC PLAYING)

969
01:04:25,732 --> 01:04:28,000
(MELLOW MUSIC CONTINUES)

970
01:04:52,558 --> 01:04:53,626
COLM: Declan!

971
01:04:59,197 --> 01:05:01,399
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATION)

972
01:05:19,785 --> 01:05:21,553
(DECLAN LAUGHING)

973
01:05:23,521 --> 01:05:25,724
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATION
CONTINUES)

974
01:05:40,806 --> 01:05:41,840
Howdo!

975
01:05:42,741 --> 01:05:43,808
Howdo!

976
01:05:43,841 --> 01:05:45,175
Do you want a ride?

977
01:05:46,678 --> 01:05:47,946
I will so.

978
01:05:47,979 --> 01:05:49,346
Thanks, fella!

979
01:05:52,249 --> 01:05:53,450
(CLICKS TONGUE)

980
01:05:58,121 --> 01:06:01,693
Oh, no, you're not that student
fella from Lisdoonvarna, are ya?

981
01:06:01,726 --> 01:06:03,293
I am. I'm Declan.

982
01:06:03,795 --> 01:06:05,162
Why?

983
01:06:05,195 --> 01:06:06,530
They told me at the
post office to try to find

984
01:06:06,563 --> 01:06:09,033
that student fella, Declan,
from Lisdoonvarna.

985
01:06:09,067 --> 01:06:10,835
Yeah, a telegram came for ya.

986
01:06:10,868 --> 01:06:12,704
From your mammy.

987
01:06:12,737 --> 01:06:14,371
My mammy is no longer with us.

988
01:06:14,404 --> 01:06:16,473
Not your mammy, sorry.
(FALTERS)

989
01:06:16,506 --> 01:06:18,810
Did I say your mammy?
Your auntie. Yeah, your auntie.

990
01:06:18,843 --> 01:06:20,210
It's about your daddy.

991
01:06:20,243 --> 01:06:21,946
What about Daddy?

992
01:06:21,980 --> 01:06:24,849
Uh, bread van crashed into him.

993
01:06:24,882 --> 01:06:26,550
The bread van?
Yeah.

994
01:06:26,583 --> 01:06:29,185
They said you'd best hurry home
to him, lest he should die all alone.

995
01:06:29,720 --> 01:06:30,754
Die?

996
01:06:30,787 --> 01:06:33,389
Or get worse, all alone.

997
01:06:35,257 --> 01:06:36,760
This is impossible.

998
01:06:36,793 --> 01:06:38,260
It's not impossible.

999
01:06:38,294 --> 01:06:40,097
Bread vans crash
into people all the time.

1000
01:06:40,129 --> 01:06:41,330
I know!

1001
01:06:41,965 --> 01:06:43,667
That's how me mammy died.

1002
01:06:46,569 --> 01:06:48,471
(JUMPS OFF)

1003
01:06:48,504 --> 01:06:51,574
If it's the same fecking
bread van, I'll kill them.

1004
01:06:59,548 --> 01:07:00,651
(TUGS REINS)

1005
01:07:08,058 --> 01:07:09,258
Thanks.

1006
01:07:11,293 --> 01:07:13,328
What were you talking
to the boat fella for?

1007
01:07:13,361 --> 01:07:15,698
For none of your fecking
business, I think it was.

1008
01:07:15,731 --> 01:07:18,067
Of course, it's me business.
Aren't I the law?

1009
01:07:18,100 --> 01:07:19,601
(SOFTLY) Fecking knob.

1010
01:07:20,002 --> 01:07:21,137
Huh?

1011
01:07:21,169 --> 01:07:22,638
Well, you can tell
that whiny brother of yours

1012
01:07:22,672 --> 01:07:25,141
I'll be around soon
for that battering I owe him.

1013
01:07:25,173 --> 01:07:26,642
A battering?

1014
01:07:26,676 --> 01:07:29,577
That'd be good, actually. It
might take him out of himself.

1015
01:07:29,611 --> 01:07:31,013
Huh?

1016
01:07:31,047 --> 01:07:33,314
You're an awful strange lady.

1017
01:07:33,916 --> 01:07:35,550
No wonder no one likes ya.

1018
01:07:37,318 --> 01:07:38,688
(PEADAR CHUCKLES)

1019
01:07:54,335 --> 01:07:56,371
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

1020
01:07:59,206 --> 01:08:00,775
(FOOTSTEPS FADE)

1021
01:08:03,712 --> 01:08:05,046
(GASPS) Oh.

1022
01:08:05,080 --> 01:08:06,580
Hello there, Mrs. McCormick.

1023
01:08:06,613 --> 01:08:11,218
A death shall come to
Inisherin afore the month is out.

1024
01:08:11,618 --> 01:08:13,154
A death, huh?

1025
01:08:13,188 --> 01:08:15,890
Maybe even two deaths.

1026
01:08:16,725 --> 01:08:17,959
Well, that'd be sad.

1027
01:08:19,460 --> 01:08:21,629
We shall pray to the Lord

1028
01:08:21,663 --> 01:08:26,233
'tis neither you, nor poor
Siobhan, will be either of them.

1029
01:08:26,266 --> 01:08:28,302
Well, is that a nice thing
to be sayin'?

1030
01:08:28,335 --> 01:08:30,638
I wasn't trying to be nice.

1031
01:08:31,405 --> 01:08:33,842
I was trying to be accurate.

1032
01:08:34,374 --> 01:08:35,910
(FOOTSTEPS RECEDING)

1033
01:08:38,012 --> 01:08:39,647
(SOFTLY) Fecking hell.

1034
01:08:47,154 --> 01:08:50,023
(SORROWFUL CLASSICAL
MUSIC PLAYING)

1035
01:09:03,137 --> 01:09:05,338
(SIOBHAN CRYING SOFTLY)

1036
01:09:12,045 --> 01:09:13,814
What's the matter?

1037
01:09:15,581 --> 01:09:16,884
Nothing.

1038
01:09:17,651 --> 01:09:18,484
(SNIFFLES)

1039
01:09:18,518 --> 01:09:20,721
(SIOBHAN BREATHING SHAKILY)

1040
01:09:28,694 --> 01:09:31,898
(SORROWFUL CLASSICAL MUSIC
CONTINUES PLAYING)

1041
01:09:42,975 --> 01:09:44,677
(DOMINIC SIGHS, MUMBLES)

1042
01:09:50,917 --> 01:09:52,785
Me daddy say
he's gonna kill you Sunday

1043
01:09:52,819 --> 01:09:54,987
for spilling the beans
about that fiddling with me.

1044
01:09:55,988 --> 01:09:57,089
(SCOFFS)

1045
01:09:59,558 --> 01:10:01,459
"Kill me," kill me,
or, you know,

1046
01:10:01,493 --> 01:10:04,197
"beat me up a bit," kill me?

1047
01:10:04,230 --> 01:10:06,699
"Beat you up a bit," kill ya,
I think.

1048
01:10:06,732 --> 01:10:08,868
Although he did kill a man once.

1049
01:10:12,838 --> 01:10:15,406
I'm sorry for that spilling
the beans on ya, Dominic.

1050
01:10:16,074 --> 01:10:18,109
I was out of order that night.

1051
01:10:18,143 --> 01:10:20,779
You was funny
apart from that bit.

1052
01:10:20,812 --> 01:10:24,182
That's why I don't understand why
that fat fella threw the finger at ya.

1053
01:10:24,216 --> 01:10:25,917
He seemed fine
when you were slagging him.

1054
01:10:25,951 --> 01:10:27,652
He did not.

1055
01:10:27,686 --> 01:10:28,887
Did he?

1056
01:10:28,920 --> 01:10:32,456
"That's the most interesting
Padraic's ever been," he said.

1057
01:10:33,557 --> 01:10:34,960
"I think I like him
again now."

1058
01:10:40,598 --> 01:10:41,733
Aye.

1059
01:10:43,235 --> 01:10:47,272
Maybe this whole thing has just
been about gettin' you to try a new tack,

1060
01:10:47,305 --> 01:10:49,107
start standin' up
for yourself a bit.

1061
01:10:50,108 --> 01:10:51,243
Do you think?

1062
01:10:51,276 --> 01:10:54,045
Yeah, and be less of a,
you know,

1063
01:10:54,079 --> 01:10:55,146
whiny little dull-arse.

1064
01:10:56,947 --> 01:10:59,283
Well, I have been less of a
whiny little dull-arse, actually.

1065
01:10:59,316 --> 01:11:00,583
Have ya, yeah?

1066
01:11:00,617 --> 01:11:02,585
Just yesterday,
there was this musician fella

1067
01:11:02,619 --> 01:11:04,520
that Colm was
getting along great with.

1068
01:11:04,554 --> 01:11:05,656
And what did I do?

1069
01:11:05,689 --> 01:11:07,124
I went and sent him
packing from the island.

1070
01:11:07,925 --> 01:11:09,425
Did ya? How?

1071
01:11:09,459 --> 01:11:11,061
I told him a bread van
crashed into his daddy,

1072
01:11:11,095 --> 01:11:13,797
and he'd have to be rushing
home to him, lest he die.

1073
01:11:17,835 --> 01:11:18,836
Oh...

1074
01:11:21,739 --> 01:11:23,874
That sounds like the
meanest thing I've ever heard.

1075
01:11:25,042 --> 01:11:26,777
Huh?

1076
01:11:26,810 --> 01:11:30,781
Well, aye,
it was a bit mean, but...

1077
01:11:32,149 --> 01:11:33,549
he'll be fine once he gets home

1078
01:11:33,583 --> 01:11:35,518
and he finds his daddy
hasn't been hit by a bread van.

1079
01:11:38,454 --> 01:11:40,757
I used to think
you were the nicest of them.

1080
01:11:42,457 --> 01:11:44,127
Turns out you're just
the same as them.

1081
01:11:44,160 --> 01:11:45,862
I am the nicest of them.

1082
01:11:48,631 --> 01:11:49,933
Ar, Dominic, now!

1083
01:11:52,567 --> 01:11:55,004
Well, maybe I'm not
a happy lad, so!

1084
01:11:56,673 --> 01:11:58,741
Maybe this is the new me!

1085
01:12:00,944 --> 01:12:01,945
Aye.

1086
01:12:03,146 --> 01:12:05,014
Maybe this is the new me.

1087
01:12:09,618 --> 01:12:11,988
(MELANCHOLY MUSIC PLAYING)

1088
01:12:39,414 --> 01:12:40,514
DOMINIC: Howdo!
(GASPS)

1089
01:12:40,548 --> 01:12:42,451
Jesus Christ, Dominic!

1090
01:12:42,483 --> 01:12:44,353
Would you ever stop
creeping up on people?

1091
01:12:44,386 --> 01:12:46,587
You almost gave me
a fecking heart attack!

1092
01:12:46,620 --> 01:12:47,723
I wasn't creeping up on ya.

1093
01:12:47,756 --> 01:12:48,857
I was sidling up on ya.

1094
01:12:48,890 --> 01:12:50,993
Between you
and that ghoul, Jesus!

1095
01:12:51,026 --> 01:12:53,895
I always call her a ghoul,
too, because she is a ghoul.

1096
01:12:53,929 --> 01:12:56,631
Jeez, we have a lot in
common, don't we? Me and you.

1097
01:12:56,665 --> 01:12:59,067
Calling old people
ghouls and that.

1098
01:13:02,104 --> 01:13:04,873
(SIGHS) It's a great old lake,
isn't it?

1099
01:13:09,609 --> 01:13:11,746
I'm glad I caught you, actually.

1100
01:13:11,779 --> 01:13:14,614
Because there was somethin' I
was wantin' to ask ya, actually.

1101
01:13:14,648 --> 01:13:17,651
And discovering how much
we have in common,

1102
01:13:17,685 --> 01:13:20,520
well, it just makes me
want to ask you even more.

1103
01:13:20,553 --> 01:13:21,956
We don't have
anything in common.

1104
01:13:21,989 --> 01:13:24,425
Uh, don't skip ahead.

1105
01:13:24,458 --> 01:13:26,894
But yeah, what I was wantin'
to ask you was...

1106
01:13:28,763 --> 01:13:30,865
Somethin' along the lines of...

1107
01:13:30,898 --> 01:13:33,501
Should've planned this, really.

1108
01:13:33,533 --> 01:13:35,736
Well, yeah, what I was wantin'
to ask you was...

1109
01:13:40,274 --> 01:13:43,543
You probably wouldn't
ever want to, I don't know,

1110
01:13:44,478 --> 01:13:46,781
to fall in love with a boy
like me, would ya?

1111
01:13:49,517 --> 01:13:52,420
Oh, Dominic,
I don't think so, love.

1112
01:13:52,453 --> 01:13:55,622
No, yeah, no.
Uh, I was thinking no.

1113
01:13:58,091 --> 01:14:01,127
Not even in the future, like?
Like when I'm your age?

1114
01:14:08,535 --> 01:14:11,938
Yeah, no, I didn't think so.

1115
01:14:11,971 --> 01:14:14,174
Just thought I'd ask
on the off chance, you know,

1116
01:14:14,207 --> 01:14:16,810
like, "faint heart" and that.
(BOTH CHUCKLE)

1117
01:14:22,382 --> 01:14:24,217
Well, there goes that dream.

1118
01:14:30,356 --> 01:14:32,025
Well,

1119
01:14:32,058 --> 01:14:35,895
I best go over there and do whatever
that thing over there I was gonna do was.

1120
01:14:36,930 --> 01:14:38,031
Mm-hmm.

1121
01:14:54,680 --> 01:14:57,683
<i>♪ I walked from Mallow Town</i>

1122
01:14:57,716 --> 01:15:00,953
<i>♪ To Aghadoe, Aghadoe</i>

1123
01:15:00,986 --> 01:15:04,723
<i>♪ I took his head
from the jail gate to Aghadoe</i>

1124
01:15:04,756 --> 01:15:06,358
Come on, Sammy,
you have to dance too.

1125
01:15:08,727 --> 01:15:12,030
<i>♪ Like an Irish king he sleeps
in Aghadoe ♪</i>

1126
01:15:12,064 --> 01:15:13,298
(DOOR SLAMS OPEN)

1127
01:15:14,099 --> 01:15:15,501
How are you, fatty?

1128
01:15:15,534 --> 01:15:16,835
Dancing with your dog, is it?

1129
01:15:16,869 --> 01:15:18,003
Well, who else
is gonna dance with ya?

1130
01:15:18,036 --> 01:15:19,638
Your poor dog
has no say in the matter.

1131
01:15:19,671 --> 01:15:21,974
And if you're too rude
to be offering me a seat,

1132
01:15:22,007 --> 01:15:24,308
I'll be taking
one of me own accord!

1133
01:15:25,943 --> 01:15:28,546
Now, how's that
for an old hello?

1134
01:15:28,579 --> 01:15:30,581
Have you gone fecking mental?

1135
01:15:30,615 --> 01:15:32,618
Have I gone fecking mental?

1136
01:15:32,650 --> 01:15:36,020
No, I haven't gone
fecking mental, actually.

1137
01:15:36,053 --> 01:15:38,089
Not only have I not gone
fecking mental,

1138
01:15:38,122 --> 01:15:40,626
but I have ten fingers to prove
I've not gone fecking mental.

1139
01:15:40,658 --> 01:15:43,327
How many fingers do you have to
prove you've not gone fecking mental?

1140
01:15:43,361 --> 01:15:44,729
Nine fingers.

1141
01:15:44,762 --> 01:15:47,098
And nine fingers
is the epitome of mental.

1142
01:15:48,499 --> 01:15:51,035
That's right. The epitome!

1143
01:15:51,068 --> 01:15:54,038
Heh. There'll be none of that!
I didn't come here for licks!

1144
01:15:54,071 --> 01:15:55,373
I came here
for the opposite of licks.

1145
01:15:55,406 --> 01:15:56,440
What's the opposite of licks?

1146
01:15:56,474 --> 01:15:57,708
Huh?

1147
01:15:58,543 --> 01:15:59,877
What did you come here for?

1148
01:15:59,911 --> 01:16:02,346
I didn't come here
for anythin', did I?

1149
01:16:02,380 --> 01:16:04,482
I just came to kick your door
in and give you a slagging.

1150
01:16:04,515 --> 01:16:06,017
Well, you've done that,
so you can go now.

1151
01:16:06,050 --> 01:16:07,884
Haven't finished yet, have I?

1152
01:16:07,918 --> 01:16:09,819
Well, I finished with your door.

1153
01:16:09,853 --> 01:16:11,755
I haven't finished
with your slagging.

1154
01:16:11,788 --> 01:16:14,191
We were doin' so well, Padraic.

1155
01:16:14,224 --> 01:16:16,092
I wasn't doing so well.

1156
01:16:18,261 --> 01:16:20,363
I was doing terrible.

1157
01:16:20,397 --> 01:16:22,165
All right, I was doin' so well.

1158
01:16:22,199 --> 01:16:24,501
Yeah, well, it can't all be
you, you, you, can it?

1159
01:16:24,534 --> 01:16:26,069
Yes, it can.

1160
01:16:26,102 --> 01:16:28,238
There's two of us in this.
No, there isn't.

1161
01:16:28,271 --> 01:16:29,573
It takes two to tango.

1162
01:16:29,606 --> 01:16:31,308
I don't want to tango.

1163
01:16:31,341 --> 01:16:33,443
Well, you danced with your dog.

1164
01:16:34,110 --> 01:16:35,212
(CLICKS TONGUE)

1165
01:16:44,955 --> 01:16:48,659
Talkin' of tangos, how's
your new tune comin' along?

1166
01:16:48,693 --> 01:16:51,094
(SIGHS) I just
finished it, actually.

1167
01:16:51,561 --> 01:16:52,761
Just this morning.

1168
01:16:53,796 --> 01:16:55,699
No, Colm, that's great, like!

1169
01:16:55,731 --> 01:16:58,133
That's why I was dancing
with me dog.

1170
01:16:58,934 --> 01:17:00,736
I don't usually dance
with me dog.

1171
01:17:00,769 --> 01:17:03,772
(CHUCKLES) There's no harm
dancin' with your dog.

1172
01:17:03,806 --> 01:17:07,343
I'd dance with me donkey
if I knew how. And she did.

1173
01:17:09,578 --> 01:17:11,046
Is it good?

1174
01:17:11,080 --> 01:17:12,248
Your tune?

1175
01:17:16,485 --> 01:17:18,954
Mm, what's it called?

1176
01:17:18,988 --> 01:17:22,091
"The Banshees of Inisherin,"
I was thinking.

1177
01:17:24,260 --> 01:17:26,929
But there are no banshees
on Inisherin.

1178
01:17:26,962 --> 01:17:29,331
I know, I just like
the double S-H sounds.

1179
01:17:30,933 --> 01:17:32,268
Aye.

1180
01:17:32,301 --> 01:17:35,137
There's plenty
of double S-H on Inisherin.

1181
01:17:35,170 --> 01:17:36,005
Yeah.

1182
01:17:36,038 --> 01:17:39,274
Maybe there are banshees, too.

1183
01:17:39,307 --> 01:17:43,177
I just don't think that they
scream to portend death anymore.

1184
01:17:43,211 --> 01:17:48,116
I think they just
sit back, amused, and observe.

1185
01:17:48,717 --> 01:17:50,084
Portend?

1186
01:17:51,152 --> 01:17:52,153
Yeah.

1187
01:17:54,723 --> 01:17:57,859
I keep having thoughts about
playing it for you at your funeral.

1188
01:17:57,892 --> 01:18:00,461
But that wouldn't be fair
on either of us, would it?

1189
01:18:09,237 --> 01:18:10,338
(GULPS)

1190
01:18:14,008 --> 01:18:17,312
Well, that's great that you
finished your tune, Colm.

1191
01:18:17,345 --> 01:18:18,880
That's more than great.

1192
01:18:19,580 --> 01:18:20,581
That's...

1193
01:18:21,882 --> 01:18:23,283
really great.

1194
01:18:31,358 --> 01:18:32,359
(COLM SIGHS)

1195
01:18:34,328 --> 01:18:38,031
(SIGHS) So, do you want
to meet me down the pub, Colm?

1196
01:18:38,832 --> 01:18:40,735
We could celebrate
your tune, like.

1197
01:18:40,768 --> 01:18:45,305
(CLOCK CHIMES TWICE)

1198
01:18:47,541 --> 01:18:49,811
Only if you'd like, like.

1199
01:18:49,843 --> 01:18:53,080
But I could run up ahead.
Order them in.

1200
01:18:55,982 --> 01:18:57,918
Why don't you do that, Padraic?

1201
01:18:59,853 --> 01:19:01,388
Why don't I run up...

1202
01:19:03,423 --> 01:19:04,558
and order them?

1203
01:19:06,392 --> 01:19:07,493
Well, I will so.

1204
01:19:10,863 --> 01:19:12,666
Jeez, that went well!
And maybe on the way,

1205
01:19:12,699 --> 01:19:15,267
I can find that student friend
of yours, that Declan fella!

1206
01:19:15,301 --> 01:19:17,103
I told him his daddy was
dying, so he'd feck off home

1207
01:19:17,136 --> 01:19:19,939
and leave us alone,
but there's no need now!

1208
01:19:19,972 --> 01:19:21,540
Sure he could join us.

1209
01:20:01,579 --> 01:20:02,947
(PADRAIC CLEARS THROAT)

1210
01:20:10,856 --> 01:20:12,357
(EXHALES, SNIFFS)

1211
01:20:14,292 --> 01:20:16,361
What are you sitting over
there for when I'm over here?

1212
01:20:16,394 --> 01:20:18,997
Just thought I'd have a sit
for meself, you know.

1213
01:20:19,899 --> 01:20:21,433
Wait for me friend.

1214
01:20:21,466 --> 01:20:23,535
Are you fecking joking me?

1215
01:20:23,568 --> 01:20:25,103
Your four-fingered friend?

1216
01:20:25,136 --> 01:20:26,639
I mean,
are you fecking joking me?

1217
01:20:26,672 --> 01:20:28,973
No, I'm not fecking joking ya.

1218
01:20:29,007 --> 01:20:31,276
He just needed
a bit of tough love was all.

1219
01:20:32,944 --> 01:20:34,512
(BARKING)

1220
01:20:47,024 --> 01:20:53,063
(CLOCK CHIMES FOUR TIMES)

1221
01:20:54,598 --> 01:20:55,633
(JONJO SIGHS)

1222
01:20:57,201 --> 01:20:59,269
(FOOTSTEPS OUTSIDE)

1223
01:21:05,777 --> 01:21:07,444
Siobhan, do you want a sherry?

1224
01:21:07,478 --> 01:21:09,112
No.
Righty-ho.

1225
01:21:10,882 --> 01:21:11,982
What are you doin'?

1226
01:21:12,015 --> 01:21:13,651
Me?
Yes, you.

1227
01:21:13,685 --> 01:21:15,185
Nothing. Just drinkin'.

1228
01:21:15,219 --> 01:21:16,754
Not waitin'?
Not waitin'.

1229
01:21:16,788 --> 01:21:18,857
Well, he is waitin', Siobhan.
He's waitin' for Colm Doherty.

1230
01:21:18,890 --> 01:21:19,924
I amn't waitin'.

1231
01:21:19,958 --> 01:21:21,457
He just told me he was waitin'.

1232
01:21:21,491 --> 01:21:23,025
Telltale!

1233
01:21:25,428 --> 01:21:29,766
Come home with me, Padraic.
I've somethin' to discuss with ya.

1234
01:21:29,800 --> 01:21:31,567
You've somethin'
to discuss with me?

1235
01:21:32,803 --> 01:21:34,504
That sounds, uh...

1236
01:21:34,537 --> 01:21:36,572
I don't want
to discuss somethin'.

1237
01:21:36,606 --> 01:21:39,776
Well, ya have to,
'cause I'm leavin'.

1238
01:21:41,277 --> 01:21:42,378
Leavin'?

1239
01:21:45,414 --> 01:21:46,617
Like leavin'?

1240
01:21:48,451 --> 01:21:49,452
Like...

1241
01:21:51,087 --> 01:21:52,321
not staying?

1242
01:21:56,727 --> 01:21:57,728
Yeah.

1243
01:22:09,639 --> 01:22:11,641
(SOMBER MUSIC PLAYING)

1244
01:22:17,847 --> 01:22:19,114
(DOOR THUDS)

1245
01:22:27,589 --> 01:22:28,590
(DOOR THUDS)

1246
01:22:29,859 --> 01:22:32,193
(SOMBER MUSIC CONTINUES)

1247
01:22:41,704 --> 01:22:42,805
But what about me?

1248
01:22:42,838 --> 01:22:44,105
What about you?

1249
01:22:44,139 --> 01:22:45,440
I'll have no friends
at all left!

1250
01:22:45,473 --> 01:22:47,877
You'll have Dominic.
Ah here!

1251
01:22:47,910 --> 01:22:49,744
And he's gone off me now, too.

1252
01:22:49,778 --> 01:22:52,379
What kind of a place is it when
the village gom goes off ya?

1253
01:22:53,113 --> 01:22:54,716
And who's gonna do the cookin'?

1254
01:22:54,749 --> 01:22:57,384
Oh, that's your first question, isn't
it? "Who's gonna do the cookin'?"

1255
01:22:57,418 --> 01:22:58,987
Well, it wasn't me
first question, was it?

1256
01:22:59,020 --> 01:23:01,288
"But what about me?"
was me first question.

1257
01:23:04,859 --> 01:23:07,194
(SOMBER MUSIC CONTINUES)

1258
01:23:34,888 --> 01:23:36,456
(SIOBHAN GASPING)

1259
01:23:36,489 --> 01:23:37,658
Padraic.

1260
01:23:39,592 --> 01:23:40,694
Padraic!

1261
01:23:43,831 --> 01:23:47,367
PADRAIC: Now?
But you can't be leavin' now!

1262
01:23:47,400 --> 01:23:49,502
I can be leavin' now.
(SNIFFLES)

1263
01:23:49,535 --> 01:23:52,171
I can't be waitin' round
for any more of this madness!

1264
01:23:52,205 --> 01:23:54,675
What the hell
did you say to him, Padraic?

1265
01:23:54,708 --> 01:23:55,909
Nothin' really.

1266
01:23:55,943 --> 01:23:57,210
(SCOFFS)

1267
01:23:57,243 --> 01:23:59,747
Well, I'd sort of had a chat
with Dominic earlier.

1268
01:23:59,780 --> 01:24:00,848
(FALTERS)

1269
01:24:00,881 --> 01:24:02,448
And a new sort of,

1270
01:24:02,482 --> 01:24:05,986
you know, standin' up for meself
sort of tack we thought I should try.

1271
01:24:06,020 --> 01:24:07,387
God!

1272
01:24:07,420 --> 01:24:10,189
It was all going fine until
he chopped off all his fingers.

1273
01:24:12,358 --> 01:24:14,862
(SNIFFLING, BREATH SHUDDERING)

1274
01:24:18,798 --> 01:24:20,800
Me books wouldn't fit.

1275
01:24:21,901 --> 01:24:24,103
Would you look
after them for me?

1276
01:24:24,137 --> 01:24:26,005
Ar, don't go, Siobhan.

1277
01:24:26,039 --> 01:24:27,907
They're all I have, really.

1278
01:24:29,842 --> 01:24:31,644
Apart from the obvious.

1279
01:24:31,678 --> 01:24:32,712
(BREATH SHUDDERS)

1280
01:24:37,516 --> 01:24:39,217
(CRIES)

1281
01:24:39,251 --> 01:24:41,688
You'll be back soon,
won't you, Siobhan?

1282
01:24:42,320 --> 01:24:45,024
(CRIES) Oh, Padraic!

1283
01:24:45,058 --> 01:24:46,893
Don't say, "Oh, Padraic."

1284
01:24:47,827 --> 01:24:49,428
Say yes.

1285
01:24:59,471 --> 01:25:01,808
(MELANCHOLY MUSIC PLAYING)

1286
01:25:19,390 --> 01:25:20,992
(SEAGULLS CALLING)

1287
01:25:21,827 --> 01:25:23,527
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

1288
01:25:38,442 --> 01:25:40,912
(MELANCHOLY MUSIC CONTINUES)

1289
01:26:19,183 --> 01:26:20,450
(MUSIC FADES)

1290
01:27:04,560 --> 01:27:06,763
(SOFT SUSPENSEFUL
MUSIC PLAYING)

1291
01:27:47,069 --> 01:27:48,871
(EXHALES HEAVILY)

1292
01:27:58,379 --> 01:27:59,748
(SNIFFLES)

1293
01:28:04,051 --> 01:28:05,119
(SMACKS LIPS)

1294
01:28:06,320 --> 01:28:07,788
Ah, Jenny.

1295
01:28:09,422 --> 01:28:10,958
(SNIFFLING)

1296
01:28:18,366 --> 01:28:19,867
(BREATHES SHAKILY)

1297
01:28:27,909 --> 01:28:28,910
(SHUDDERS)

1298
01:28:38,219 --> 01:28:39,519
(SIGHS)

1299
01:28:42,990 --> 01:28:44,557
(SNIFFLING)

1300
01:28:47,761 --> 01:28:48,762
Oh.

1301
01:28:52,531 --> 01:28:55,101
(MELANCHOLY OPERATIC
MUSIC PLAYING)

1302
01:30:17,382 --> 01:30:18,582
(SIGHS)

1303
01:30:53,184 --> 01:30:54,685
I don't want to talk.

1304
01:30:55,386 --> 01:30:57,355
Don't go killin' his dog now.

1305
01:30:57,388 --> 01:30:58,523
And don't be puttin' things
in me head

1306
01:30:58,555 --> 01:30:59,724
that weren't there
in the first feckin' place,

1307
01:30:59,757 --> 01:31:01,525
you feckin' nutbag!

1308
01:31:02,359 --> 01:31:04,127
(CHUCKLING) "Nutbag!"

1309
01:31:06,196 --> 01:31:08,198
(BROODING MUSIC PLAYING)

1310
01:31:57,113 --> 01:31:59,148
What would I ever hurt you for?

1311
01:32:00,816 --> 01:32:02,952
You're the only nice thing
about him.

1312
01:32:09,291 --> 01:32:11,694
(LIVELY FOLK MUSIC PLAYING)

1313
01:32:12,895 --> 01:32:15,197
(SCATTING ALONG TO MUSIC)

1314
01:32:25,609 --> 01:32:26,809
(COLM LAUGHS)

1315
01:32:32,580 --> 01:32:34,983
How are you, Padraic?
You're lookin' well.

1316
01:32:42,757 --> 01:32:44,125
That's lovely, lads.

1317
01:32:48,997 --> 01:32:51,132
I don't need your apologies,
all right?

1318
01:32:51,666 --> 01:32:53,535
It's a relief to me.

1319
01:32:53,568 --> 01:32:55,069
So, let's just call it quits

1320
01:32:55,103 --> 01:32:58,106
and agree to go our separate
ways, for good this time.

1321
01:33:00,875 --> 01:33:03,778
Your fat fingers
killed me little donkey today.

1322
01:33:03,811 --> 01:33:06,814
So, no, we won't call it quits.

1323
01:33:06,848 --> 01:33:08,049
We'll call it the start.

1324
01:33:09,017 --> 01:33:10,685
You're jokin' me.
Yeah, no.

1325
01:33:10,718 --> 01:33:12,655
I'm not jokin' ya.

1326
01:33:12,687 --> 01:33:14,656
So tomorrow, Sunday,

1327
01:33:14,721 --> 01:33:17,090
God's day, around 2:00,

1328
01:33:17,124 --> 01:33:19,526
I'm going to call up to your
house and I'm gonna set fire to it,

1329
01:33:19,560 --> 01:33:21,828
and hopefully
you'll still be inside it.

1330
01:33:22,763 --> 01:33:24,831
But I won't be checkin'
either way.

1331
01:33:27,568 --> 01:33:29,369
Just be sure
and leave your dog outside.

1332
01:33:30,605 --> 01:33:32,773
I've nothing against that gom.

1333
01:33:34,341 --> 01:33:37,844
Or you can do whatever's
in your power to stop me.

1334
01:33:40,981 --> 01:33:43,217
To our graves we're taking this.

1335
01:33:44,751 --> 01:33:46,720
To one of our graves, anyways.

1336
01:33:48,555 --> 01:33:49,823
PEADAR: Here.

1337
01:33:49,856 --> 01:33:51,925
I've a bone to pick
with you, dreary.

1338
01:33:51,959 --> 01:33:53,794
Is that little gobshite
of mine at your place again?

1339
01:33:53,827 --> 01:33:55,996
Leave him, Peadar.
His donkey's just died.

1340
01:33:56,396 --> 01:33:57,599
Did he?

1341
01:33:57,632 --> 01:33:59,131
The little miniature fella?

1342
01:33:59,165 --> 01:34:01,867
Well, Jesus, boys,
I'll tell ya this much...

1343
01:34:13,813 --> 01:34:15,114
Two o'clock.

1344
01:34:20,786 --> 01:34:22,188
(DOOR CLOSES)

1345
01:34:26,593 --> 01:34:29,128
(SOMBER MUSIC PLAYING)
(BELL TOLLING)

1346
01:34:43,508 --> 01:34:45,510
(PRIEST PRAYING IN LATIN)

1347
01:35:11,503 --> 01:35:12,570
(PARTITION SLIDES)

1348
01:35:15,373 --> 01:35:16,609
(CLICKS TONGUE SOFTLY)

1349
01:35:16,642 --> 01:35:18,410
I killed a miniature donkey.

1350
01:35:22,514 --> 01:35:24,182
It was by accident...

1351
01:35:27,185 --> 01:35:29,053
but I do feel bad about it.

1352
01:35:31,388 --> 01:35:35,926
Do you think God gives a damn
about miniature donkeys, Colm?

1353
01:35:37,762 --> 01:35:39,196
I fear he doesn't.

1354
01:35:41,965 --> 01:35:44,501
And I fear that's where
it's all gone wrong.

1355
01:35:46,937 --> 01:35:48,172
Is that it?

1356
01:35:49,206 --> 01:35:51,075
Is what it?

1357
01:35:51,108 --> 01:35:53,043
Aren't you forgetting
a couple of things?

1358
01:35:54,511 --> 01:35:57,214
No, I think I've covered it.

1359
01:35:57,247 --> 01:36:00,984
(SIGHS) Wouldn't you say
punching a policeman is a sin?

1360
01:36:01,820 --> 01:36:03,688
Ah here.

1361
01:36:03,722 --> 01:36:05,790
If punching a policeman
is a sin,

1362
01:36:05,824 --> 01:36:09,026
we may as well just
pack up and go home.

1363
01:36:10,527 --> 01:36:12,962
And self-mutilation is a sin.

1364
01:36:13,731 --> 01:36:15,164
It's one of the biggest.

1365
01:36:15,833 --> 01:36:17,166
Is it?

1366
01:36:17,200 --> 01:36:20,403
Self-mutilation,
so you have me there.

1367
01:36:20,436 --> 01:36:22,038
Multiplied by five.

1368
01:36:27,377 --> 01:36:29,245
How's the despair?

1369
01:36:33,717 --> 01:36:35,184
It's back a bit.

1370
01:36:37,954 --> 01:36:40,156
But you're not gonna
do anything about it?

1371
01:36:44,160 --> 01:36:46,663
I'm not gonna
do anything about it, no.

1372
01:36:53,936 --> 01:36:56,139
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING)

1373
01:37:01,176 --> 01:37:02,944
SIOBHAN: <i>Dear Padraic,</i>

1374
01:37:02,978 --> 01:37:07,482
<i>I am safely ensconced in the
mainland and, Padraic, it's lovely here.</i>

1375
01:37:07,516 --> 01:37:10,318
<i>There's a river running
past my window as I write,</i>

1376
01:37:10,352 --> 01:37:12,988
<i>and the people already seem
less bitter and mental.</i>

1377
01:37:13,021 --> 01:37:17,559
<i>I'm not sure why, but I think it's
'cause a lot of them are from Spain.</i>

1378
01:37:17,593 --> 01:37:21,096
<i>Mostly, I wanted to say there's a
spare bed here for you, Padraic.</i>

1379
01:37:21,129 --> 01:37:25,333
<i>And with the war almost over, I
think there'd be work for ya here.</i>

1380
01:37:25,367 --> 01:37:28,036
<i>Because there's nothing
for you on Inisherin.</i>

1381
01:37:28,069 --> 01:37:30,640
<i>Nothing but more
bleakness and grudges</i>

1382
01:37:30,673 --> 01:37:33,308
<i>and loneliness and spite</i>

1383
01:37:33,341 --> 01:37:36,311
<i>and the slow passing of time
until death.</i>

1384
01:37:36,344 --> 01:37:38,380
<i>And sure,
you can do that anywhere.</i>

1385
01:37:41,116 --> 01:37:44,318
<i>So come, Padraic. Leave there.</i>

1386
01:37:44,351 --> 01:37:47,221
<i>Dominic can look after Jenny
and the rest of your animals.</i>

1387
01:37:47,254 --> 01:37:49,557
<i>They could move
into the house together.</i>

1388
01:37:49,591 --> 01:37:52,026
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING)

1389
01:37:59,333 --> 01:38:00,334
Hut!

1390
01:38:22,022 --> 01:38:25,192
SIOBHAN: <i>So come now,
Padraic, please.</i>

1391
01:38:28,762 --> 01:38:31,164
<i>Before it's all too late.</i>

1392
01:38:50,316 --> 01:38:52,753
(SENTIMENTAL OPERATIC
MUSIC PLAYING)

1393
01:39:49,842 --> 01:39:53,245
(CLOCK CHIMES TWICE)
(PANTING)

1394
01:40:17,703 --> 01:40:19,705
(MELANCHOLY MUSIC PLAYING)

1395
01:40:56,741 --> 01:40:57,875
(COWBELL JINGLES)

1396
01:41:09,252 --> 01:41:10,487
(SCRATCHING ON DOOR)

1397
01:41:11,722 --> 01:41:12,723
(SNAPS FINGERS)

1398
01:41:21,832 --> 01:41:23,500
PADRAIC: <i>Dear Siobhan.</i>

1399
01:41:23,533 --> 01:41:26,568
<i>Obviously, I don't know
what "ensconced" is,</i>

1400
01:41:26,603 --> 01:41:30,305
<i>but I thank you for the offer of
the free bed and the whatnot.</i>

1401
01:41:30,339 --> 01:41:32,809
<i>But I won't be takin' you up
on it, I'm afraid.</i>

1402
01:41:33,810 --> 01:41:36,980
<i>As I told you,
me life is on Inisherin.</i>

1403
01:41:37,013 --> 01:41:38,948
<i>Me friends, me animals.</i>

1404
01:41:42,819 --> 01:41:43,887
<i>Even now as I write,</i>

1405
01:41:43,920 --> 01:41:46,122
<i>little donkey Jenny
is looking at me, saying,</i>

1406
01:41:46,156 --> 01:41:48,725
<i>"Please don't go, Padraic.
We'd miss ya."</i>

1407
01:41:48,758 --> 01:41:51,661
<i>And nuzzling me,
the gilly-gooly.</i>

1408
01:41:52,294 --> 01:41:53,797
<i>Get off, Jenny.</i>

1409
01:41:57,167 --> 01:41:58,367
MRS. McCORMICK: Psst!

1410
01:42:08,144 --> 01:42:09,945
PADRAIC: <i>In other news,</i>

1411
01:42:09,978 --> 01:42:12,480
<i>in sadder news, actually,</i>

1412
01:42:12,513 --> 01:42:15,316
<i>I won't be able to ask Dominic
anything, I'm afraid.</i>

1413
01:42:17,318 --> 01:42:19,888
<i>Because they found him
in the lake this morning.</i>

1414
01:42:23,926 --> 01:42:27,361
<i>I suppose he must've slipped
and fell in.</i>

1415
01:42:35,137 --> 01:42:38,372
<i>So, there'd be no one to take
care of the animals, anyway.</i>

1416
01:42:54,223 --> 01:42:56,591
(GLASS SMASHING)

1417
01:43:01,495 --> 01:43:03,563
<i>No other news, really.</i>

1418
01:43:12,506 --> 01:43:14,742
<i>Except that I love you, Siobhan.</i>

1419
01:43:15,877 --> 01:43:17,011
<i>And I miss ya.</i>

1420
01:43:19,412 --> 01:43:21,783
<i>And I hope I'll see ya
again someday.</i>

1421
01:43:24,351 --> 01:43:26,286
<i>If you ever come back home.</i>

1422
01:43:29,023 --> 01:43:31,324
Come back home, Siobhan.

1423
01:43:36,197 --> 01:43:39,331
<i>Yours sincerely,
your loving brother...</i>

1424
01:43:41,234 --> 01:43:42,869
<i>Padraic Suilleabhain.</i>

1425
01:43:54,014 --> 01:43:55,982
(SOMBER MUSIC PLAYING)

1426
01:44:32,051 --> 01:44:33,351
(BARKS)

1427
01:44:56,108 --> 01:44:59,444
(WAVES CRASHING)

1428
01:45:16,728 --> 01:45:18,930
Suppose me house makes us quits.

1429
01:45:20,665 --> 01:45:23,735
If you'd stayed in your house,
that would've made us quits.

1430
01:45:23,768 --> 01:45:26,536
But you didn't, did ya,
so it doesn't, does it?

1431
01:45:37,949 --> 01:45:40,450
I'm sorry
about your donkey, Padraic.

1432
01:45:40,952 --> 01:45:42,486
Honestly, I am.

1433
01:45:44,956 --> 01:45:46,791
I don't fucking care.

1434
01:46:02,306 --> 01:46:05,809
Haven't heard any rifle fire
from the mainland in a day or two.

1435
01:46:05,842 --> 01:46:08,712
I think they're coming
to the end of it.

1436
01:46:08,745 --> 01:46:12,049
I'm sure they'll be at it again
soon enough, aren't you?

1437
01:46:13,784 --> 01:46:16,086
Some things
there's no movin' on from.

1438
01:46:19,256 --> 01:46:21,058
And I think that's a good thing.

1439
01:46:43,746 --> 01:46:44,880
Padraic.

1440
01:46:50,786 --> 01:46:53,656
Thanks for lookin' after
me dog for me, anyways.

1441
01:46:59,795 --> 01:47:00,930
Any time.

1442
01:47:16,479 --> 01:47:18,681
(SCATTING)

1443
01:47:34,863 --> 01:47:37,832
(SENTIMENTAL OPERATIC
MUSIC PLAYING)

1444
01:49:25,938 --> 01:49:28,141
(INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC PLAYING)

